## Migration: `BackgroundProcessor` → .NET 8 Cooperative Cancellation

### Pattern Classification

| Usage | Pattern | Replacement |
|-------|---------|-------------|
| `while (_running)` loop | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationToken` |
| `_workerThread.Abort()` | Force stop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Cleanup on abort | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Remove — cooperative model doesn't need it |

---

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — same logic as the old ThreadAbortException block
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — we simply exit the loop naturally
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        _cts.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

---

### Key Changes Explained

1. **`Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()`** — signals the token; the loop checks it cooperatively.

2. **`Thread.Sleep(2000)` → `Thread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2))`** — actually waits for the thread to exit rather than sleeping blindly.

3. **`catch (ThreadAbortException)` → `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)`** — the `when` filter ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not unrelated OCEs.

4. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` → removed** — cooperative cancellation doesn't auto-rethrow; you control flow normally.

5. **`GetNextItem()` must accept a token** — this is critical. If it blocks (e.g., on a `BlockingCollection`), pass the token so it can unblock:
   ```csharp
   private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
   {
       // Example: BlockingCollection supports cancellation natively
       return _queue.Take(token);
   }
   ```

---

### Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| Not passing token to `GetNextItem` | If the method blocks indefinitely, `Cancel()` won't unblock it — your `Stop()` hangs past the 2s join |
| Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource` | Leaks internal timers and registered callbacks |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` without `when` filter | May accidentally swallow cancellations from unrelated tokens (e.g., HTTP request timeouts) |
| Removing cleanup logic from the catch block | The old `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` was critical — keep it in the new catch or move to `finally` |
| Assuming cancellation is instant | It only fires at the next checkpoint (`IsCancellationRequested` check or token-aware API call) |
